eben) In Kalakad-Mundanthurai Tiger Reserve, Tamil Nadu, India.\" ''Current Science (00113891)'' 95.7 (2008): 889\u2013894. ''Academic Search Premier''. Web. 3 Nov. 2015\n*Jathanna, Devcharan, N. Samba Kumar, and K. Ullas Karanth. [https://web.archive.org/web/20190403150614/http://repository.ias.ac.in/89462/1/23P.pdf \"Measuring Indian Giant Squirrel (Ratufa Indica) Abundance In Southern India Using Distance Sampling.\"] ''Current Science (00113891)'' 95.7 (2008): 885\u2013888. ''Academic Search Premier''. Web. 3 Nov. 2015.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ratufa indica}}\n\n{{S. Ratufinae-Sciurillinae nav}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2668978}}\n\n[[Category:Ratufa]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Asia]]\n[[Category:Rodents of India]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1777]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of India]]\n[[Category:Symbols of Maharashtra]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Indian giant squirrel\n| image = Ratufa indica (Bhadra, 2006).jpg\n| image_caption = ''R. i. indica'' in [[Bhadra Wildlife Sanctuary]], [[Karnataka]], India\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn|author=Rajamani, N.|author2=Molur, S.|author3=Nameer, P. O.|last-author-amp=yes|year=2010|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/19378/0|title=''Ratufa indica''|access-date=22 June 2012|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Ratufa\n| species = indica\n| authority = ([[Johann Christian Polycarp Erxleben|Erxleben]], 1777)\n| subdivision_ranks = Subspecies\n| subdivision_ref = <ref name=\"Thorington\">{{cite book|last1=Thorington|first1=R.W. Jr.|last2=Hoffmann|first2=R.S.|year=2005|pages=754\u2013818|editor1-last=Wilson|editor1-first=D.E.|editor2-last=Reeder|editor2-first=D.M|url=http://www.bucknell.edu/msw3|chapter=Ratufa indica|chapterurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120913012408/http://www.bucknell.edu/msw3/browse.asp?id=12400025|title=Mammal Species of the World: a taxonomic and geographic reference|edition=3rd|publisher=The Johns Hopkins University Press|isbn=0-8018-8221-4|oclc=26158608}}</ref>\n| subdivision =\n* ''R. i. indica''\n* ''R. i. centralis''\n* ''R. i. dealbata''\n* ''R. i. maxima''\n| range_map = Ratufa indica range map.svg\n| range_map_caption = Indian giant squirrel range\n}}\n\nThe '''Indian giant squirrel''', or '''Malabar giant squirrel''', (''Ratufa indica'') is a large [[tree squirrel]] species in the genus ''[[Ratufa]]'' native to forests and woodlands in [[India]]. It is a [[Diurnal animal|diurnal]], [[arboreal]], and mainly [[herbivorous]] [[squirrel]].<ref name=datta_p394>{{Harv|Datta|Goyal|1996|p=394}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThis species is [[Endemism|endemic]] to India, with main sections of its distribution in the [[Western Ghats]], [[Eastern Ghats]] and [[Satpura Range]] as far north as [[Madhya Pradesh]] (approximately [[22nd parallel north|22\u00b0 N]]).<ref name=iucn/><ref name=datta_p394/> It is found at altitudes of {{cvt|180-2300|m|ft}} in tropical [[deciduous]], [[semi-deciduous]] (where often utilizing denser [[Riparian forest|riparian growth]]), and moist [[evergreen]] forests and woodlands.<ref name=iucn/><ref name=datta_p394/><ref name=Thorington2012>{{cite book | author1=Thorington, Jr., R.W. | author2=J.L. Koprowski | author3=M.A. Steele | author4=J.F. Whatton | year=2012 | title=Squirrels of the World | pages=26\u201327 | publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press | location=Baltimore | isbn=978-1-4214-0469-1 }}</ref> In general, its distribution is fragmented because it is intolerant of habitat degradation.<ref name=iucn/> The Indian Giant Squirrel generally nests in taller trees with a mean height of 11.08 (+/- 2.8 SD) in order to avoid predators.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pradhan |first1=A.K. |last2=Shrotriya |first2=S. |last3=Rout |first3=S.D. |last4=Dash |first4=P.K. |title=Nesting and feeding habits of the Indian giant squirrel (Ratufa indica) in Karlapat wildlife sanctuary, India |journal=Animal and Biodiversity Conservation |volume=40.1}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Ratufa indica maxima.jpg|thumb|left|''R. i. maxima'' in [[Kerala]]]]\n\nThe Indian giant squirrel is one of the largest squirrels with a head\u2013and\u2013body length of {{cvt|25-50|cm|ftin|0}}, a tail that is about the same or somewhat longer, and a weight of {{cvt|1.5-2|kg|lb}}, although rarely up to {{cvt|3|kg|lb}}.<ref name=Walker1999>{{cite book| editor=Nowak, R.M.| year=1999 | title= Walker's Mammals of the World | volume=2 | edition= 6 | pages=1274\u20131275 | isbn=978-0-8018-5789-8 }}</ref><ref name=Abdulali1952>{{cite journal | author1=Abdulali, H. | author2=J.C. Daniel | year=1952 | title=Races of the Indian Giant Squirrel (Ratufa indica) | journal=The Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society | volume=50 | pages=469\u2013474 }}</ref> Average for both sexes is about {{cvt|36|cm|ftin}} in head\u2013and\u2013body length, {{cvt|45|cm|ftin}} in tail length and {{cvt|1.7-1.8|kg|lb}} in weight.<ref name=Thorington2012/>\n\nIt has a conspicuous one-, two- or three-toned colour scheme.<ref name=tritsch>{{Harvnb|Tritsch|2001|pp=132\u2013133}}</ref> The colours involved can be whitish, [[cream (color)|creamy]]-[[beige]], [[buff (color)|buff]], [[tan (color)|tan]], [[rust (color)|rust]], reddish-[[maroon]], brown, a dark [[seal brown]] or black.<ref name=Thorington2012/><ref name=prater24-25>{{Harvnb|Prater|1971|pp=24\u201325}}</ref> The underparts and the front legs are usually cream coloured, the head can be brown or beige, however there is a distinctive white spot between the ears.<ref name=tritsch/> Otherwise the colours depend on the [[subspecies]].<ref name=Thorington2012/>\n\n===Subspecies===\n{{multiple image | direction = horizontal | image1 = Sciurus indicusJBNHS.jpg | image2 = Sciurus indicus malabaricus.jpg | width1 = 148 | width2 = 150 | footer = <br><!--necessary to maintain format-->\n*''R. i. dealbatus'' (top left)\n*''R. i. indica'' (below left)\n*\"''R. i. bengalensis''\" (=''R. i. indica\u2013maxima'' intergrade; top right)\n*''R. i. maxima'' (below right)\n}}\n\nTen subspecies have been described,<ref name=Abdulali1952/> but recent authorities generally recognise four:<ref name=Thorington2012/><ref name=Corbet1992>{{cite book|last1=Corbet|first1=Gordon Barclay|last2=Hill|first2=John Edwards|title=The mammals of the Indomalayan Region:a systematic review|year=1992|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|isbn=0-19-854693-9|oclc=25281229}}</ref><ref name=\"Rajamani\">{{Cite iucn|last=Rajamani|first=Nandini |author2=Sanjay Molur |author3=P. Ommer Nameer|title=Ratufa indica|year=2008|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/19378/0|accessdate =24 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n*''R. i. indica'': Found in the northern and central Western Ghats from around [[Mumbai]] to [[Karnataka]]. Its upper parts and basal half of the tail are rich reddish-maroon or reddish-brown; the distal part of the tail is whitish or buff.<ref name=Thorington2012/><ref name=Abdulali1952/> On occasion there can be some black at the shoulder or at the very base of the tail (features typically associated with other subspecies).<ref name=Abdulali1952/> A few other subspecies have been described within its range based on variations in size, overall colour hue and width of the pale tail-tip,<ref name=Abdulali1952/> but recent authorities generally regard them as [[Synonym (biology)|synonyms]] of ''R. i. indica''.<ref name=\"Thorington\" />\n\n*''R. i. centralis'': From central and eastern India, notably in the Satpura Range and Eastern Ghats (all other subspecies are from the Western Ghats region). It is relatively small and further differs from ''R. i. indica'' by its black shoulder region, black tail except for the pale tip, and sometimes black rump.<ref name=Thorington2012/><ref name=Abdulali1952/>\n\n*''R. i. dealbata'': Found in southern [[Gujarat]] (far northern Western Ghats region),<ref name=Abdulali1952/> but recent surveys have failed to locate it,<ref name=iucn/> and it is possibly [[extinct]].<ref name=Thorington2012/> A highly distinctive pale subspecies that is overall creamy-buff with a whitish tail and brown ears.<ref name=Abdulali1952/> It should not be confused with true [[albino]]s, rarely recorded in the Indian giant squirrel, which are whiter and have pink eyes unlike ''R. i. dealbata''.<ref name=Abdulali1953>{{cite journal | author1=Abdulali, H. | author2=J.C. Daniel | year=1953 | title=A colour variation, and albinism in the giant squirrel Ratufa indica | journal=The Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society | volume=51 | page=731 }}</ref>\n\n*''R. i. maxima'': From southern Western Ghats. It resembles a large ''R. i. centralis'', but with more extensive black in the shoulder region and on the rump, and an almost entirely black tail (no pale tip). There is often a black dorsal stripe connecting the black shoulder region and rump. Another subspecies, ''R. i. bengalensis'', has been described from southern Karnataka and northern [[Kerala]], in between ''R. i. indica'' and ''R. i. maxima''. It generally resembles ''R. i. indica'', but the tail is black except for its pale tip and sometimes it has black shoulders, thus approaching ''R. i. maxima'' or ''R. i. centralis''.<ref name=Abdulali1952/> Its intermediate appearance and distribution has caused some questions about its validity; it could be regarded as an [[intergrade]] and recent authorities often treat it as a synonym of ''R. i. maxima''.<ref name=Corbet1992/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ '''''Ratufa indica''''' '''taxonomy'''<ref name=\"Thorington\" />\n|-\n! Subspecies\n! Authority\n! Synonyms\n|-\n| ''R. i. indica''\n| [[Johann Christian Polycarp Erxleben|Erxleben]], 1777<ref name=\"Erxleben\">{{cite book |last1=Erxleben|first1=Johann Christian Polykarp|title=Systema regni animalis per classes, ordines, genera, species, varietates cum synonymia et historia animalium. Classis I. Mammalia.|trans-title=Animal kingdom system by class, order, genus, species, varieties with synonyms and animals' history. Class I. Mammalia.|volume=42|year=1777|publisher=Impensis Weygandianis|location=Leipzig, Germany|language=Latin|oclc=14843832}}</ref>\n| ''bombaya'', ''elphinstoni'', ''purpureus'', ''superans''\n|-\n| ''R. i. centralis''\n| Ryley, 1913<ref name=\"Ryley\">{{cite journal|last1=Ryley|first1=Kathleen V.|date=1913|title=Scientific results from the mammals survey|journal=The Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society|volume=22|pages=434\u2013443|publisher=Bombay Natural History Society|location=Mumbai, India|issn=0006-6982|oclc=1536710}}</ref>\n| none\n|-\n| ''R. i. dealbata''\n| [[William Thomas Blanford|Blanford]], 1897\n| none\n|-\n| ''R. i. maxima''\n| [[Johann Christian Daniel von Schreber|Schreber]], 1784<ref name=\"Schreber\">{{cite book|last1=Schreber|first1=Johann Christian Daniel von|title=Die S\u00e4ugthiere in Abbildungen nach der Natur, mit Beschreibungen |trans-title=The S\u00e4ugthiere in illustrations after nature, with descriptions|volume=3|year=1792|origyear=Chapter on The Squirrel first published in 1784|publisher=Wolfgang Walther|location=Erlangen|language=German|oclc=16860541|trans-chapter=The Squirrel|chapter=Der Springer}}</ref>\n| ''bengalensis'', ''malabarica''\n|}\n\n==Behaviour==\n[[File:Ratufa indica and jack fruit.JPG|thumb|Malabar giant squirrels feeding on a ripe [[jackfruit]] in [[Nagarhole National Park]], Karnataka]]\n[[File:Giant squirrel loving banana.jpg|thumb|''R. i. centralis'' eating a banana, [[Tirupati]] hills, [[Andhra Pradesh]]|upright]]\n\nThe Indian giant squirrel is an upper-canopy dwelling species, which rarely leaves the trees, and requires \"tall profusely branched trees for the construction of nests.\"<ref name=datta_p394/>  It travels from tree to tree with jumps of up to {{convert|6|m|ft|abbr=on}}. When in danger, the ''Ratufa indica'' often freezes or flattens itself against the tree trunk, instead of fleeing.<ref name=tritsch/> Its main predators are the [[birds of prey]] and the [[leopard]].<ref name=tritsch/> The Giant Squirrel is mostly active in the early hours of the morning and in the evening, resting in the midday. They are typically solitary animals that only come together for breeding. The species is believed to play a substantial role in shaping the ecosystem of its habitat by engaging in seed dispersal.<ref name=animaldiversity>{{cite web|url=http://animaldiversity.org/accounts/Ratufa_indica/|title=Ratufa indica: Indian Giant Squirrel|last=Justice|first=James|accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref> Diet includes fruit, flowers, nuts and tree bark.  Some subspecies are omnivorous, also eating insects and bird eggs.<ref name=\"Indian Giant Squirrel\">{{cite web |url=http://www.arkive.org/indian-giant-squirrel/ratufa-indica/video-08.html |title=Indian giant squirrel (Ratufa indica) |publisher=Arkive |access-date=25 February 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113101000/http://www.arkive.org/indian-giant-squirrel/ratufa-indica/video-08.html |archive-date=13 January 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Family life===\nThe Indian Giant Squirrel lives alone or in pairs. They build large globular nests of twigs and leaves, placing them on thinner branches where large predators can't get to them. These nests become conspicuous in deciduous forests during the dry season. An individual may build several nests in a small area of forest which are used as sleeping quarters, with one being used as a nursery.{{Citation needed|date=November 2010}}\n\n===Reproduction===\nCaptive breeding of the [[Black giant squirrel|Malayan giant squirrel]], a close relative has indicated births in March, April, September and December. The young weigh 74.5 g at birth and have a length of 27.3&nbsp;cm. In Canara, the Indian Giant Squirrel has been spotted with young in March. {{Citation needed|date=November 2010}}\n\n==Recognition==\nIndian Giant Squirrel (''Shekaru'' in [[Marathi language|Marathi]]) is the [[state animal]] of the state of [[Maharashtra]] in western India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jagranjosh.com/general-knowledge/list-of-indian-states-and-their-symbols-1482840512-1|title=List of Indian States and their Symbols|date=2017-08-14|website=www.jagranjosh.com|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Citation\n | last1=Blanford\n | first1=W. T.\n | title=The large Indian squirrel (''Sciurus indicus erx.'') and its local races and sub-species\n | journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society\n |volume=11\n |issue=2\n | year=1897\n | pages=298\u2013305\n | url=\n }}\n*{{Citation\n | last1=Borges\n | first1=Renee M.\n | authorlink = Renee M. Borges\n | title=Figs, Malabar Giant Squirrels, and Fruit Shortages Within Two Tropical Indian Forests\n | journal=Biotropica\n |volume=25\n |issue=2\n | year=1993\n | pages=183\u2013190\n | jstor=2389182\n | doi=10.2307/2389182\n | url=http://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/19bd/e89931cee405ad3f2d6b2e641f93d756774c.pdf\n }}\n*{{Citation\n | last1=Datta\n | first1=Aparajita\n | last2=Goyal\n | first2=S. P.\n | title=Comparison of Forest Structure and Use by the Indian Giant Squirrel (''Ratufa indica'') in Two Riverine Forests of Central India\n | journal=Biotropica\n |volume=28\n |issue=3\n | year=1996\n | pages=394\u2013399\n | jstor=2389203\n | doi=10.2307/2389203\n }}\n*{{Citation\n | last1=Moore\n | first1=Joseph Curtis\n | title=Squirrel Geography of the Indian Subregion\n | journal=Systematic Zoology\n |volume=9\n |issue=1\n | year=1960\n | pages=1\u201317\n | jstor=2411536\n | doi=10.2307/2411536\n }}\n*{{Citation\n | last1=Prater\n | first1=S. H.\n | authorlink=Stanley Henry Prater\n | year=1971\n | title=The book of Indian Animals\n | place=\n | publisher=Mumbai: Bombay Natural History Society and Oxford University Press. Pp. xxiii, 324, 28 color plates by Paul Barruel.\n | isbn=0-19-562169-7\n | url=\n }}\n*{{Citation\n | last1=Somanathan\n | first1=Hema\n | last2=Mali\n | first2=Subhash\n | last3=Bo